                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>It's my party, and I won't cry if I (don't) want  to:</em></strong><em>&nbsp; The  continuing UWB standards war took a new twist this month as Freescale, the  Motorola spin-off that formed one of the two rival organizations that led a  IEEE working group to give up on setting a standard&hellip;quit its own organization,  giving the scribes much to write about.&nbsp;  At the same time, the Bluetooth SIG plighted its troth to the specification  offered by the rival group.&nbsp; Is that the  end of the road for Freescale?&nbsp;  &quot;Just a flesh wound,&quot; according to Calvin Harrison, a  spokesperson for Freescale, sounding rather like the steadily diminishing  knight in Monty Python's Spamalot.</em></p>                      </td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.techworld.com/mobility/news/index.cfm?newsID=5756&pagtype=samechan" target="_hdl">Freescale flounces out of own UWB  club</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Peter Judge</strong><br>
                <strong>Techworld April 11, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Silicon maker Freescale, having lost every  single competition for the nascent super-fast ultra-wideband (UWB) technology,  has left the only club that would still have it - the UWB Forum, which it set  up itself. Freescale's version of UWB has been passed over, in favour of the  Intel-backed WiMedia flavour, for wireless USB, and (last week) for super-fast  Bluetooth, both of which will give connection speeds of around 500 Mbit/s for  devices. <a href="http://www.techworld.com/mobility/news/index.cfm?newsID=5756&pagtype=samechan">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style10"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20060329-6488.html" target="_hdl">Bluetooth chooses its ultrawideband future</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Peter Pollack</strong><br>
                <strong>Ars Technica April 2, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Bluetooth SIG has announced that it is  adopting the WiMedia Alliance version of ultrawideband (UWB) as its future  standard, over that of the competing variant proposed by the UWB Forum. The  group had previously announced that it would be embracing UWB, which is  considered the next stage of short-range wireless technology. UWB can  theoretically provide data transmission rates of several hundred Mb/s over  short distances with very low power consumption. <a href="http://arstechnica.com/news.ars/post/20060329-6488.html">...Full Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style10"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.futura-sciences.com/newsrss-ultra-wideband-plus-usb-q-with-calvin-harrison-freescale-semiconductor_161769.php">Ultra-Wideband  plus USB: Q&amp;A with Calvin Harrison, Freescale Semiconductor</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Chris Hall</strong><br>
                <strong>DigiTimes.com April 10, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The marriage of Ultra-Wideband and USB  remains a tantalizing vision for the communications industry, although perhaps  a marriage made in hell as much as in heaven. The IT and communications  industries have long regarded Ultra Wideband (UWB) as a technology of great  promise but delayed by a battle over an IEEE 802.15.3a standard between,  basically, Freescale (and Motorola) on the one hand and Intel on the  other....One of the technologies &quot;riding&quot; on UWB is Wireless USB,  which again has devolved into a standards war, with Freescale proposing  Cable-Free USB and the Intel /MBOA Alliance camp supporting Certified Wireless  USB. ...<a href="http://www.futura-sciences.com/newsrss-ultra-wideband-plus-usb-q-with-calvin-harrison-freescale-semiconductor_161769.php">Full  Story</a></p>
              <div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></div>
              <p align="left" class="style10">Semantic and NextGen Web</p>
              <table width="508"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td colspan="2" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>The one down side to  [Google's new calendar] program is, you have to be online when you use it</em></strong></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td width="46" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td width="455" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p>Subtle observation of  Chris Sherman, executive editor of Search Engine Watch&hellip;<a href="http://news.com.com/2100-1032_3-6060741.html">Full Story</a></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <table width="605"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>Nobody ever said that this would be easy:</em></strong><em>&nbsp; It's now been almost a year since I did an  in-depth <a href="http://www.consortiuminfo.org/bulletins/jun05.php#feature">interview  with Tim Berners-Lee</a> focusing on the challenges of rolling out the Semantic  Web.&nbsp; Since then, two things haven't  changed.&nbsp; The first is that it's still  hard to explain the Semantic Web to the world in order to get them on the bus,  as noted in the first article below.&nbsp;  And the second is that those that &quot;get&quot; the Semantic Web the  best and are most motivated to implement it are those dealing with specific  domains of data that they wish to share with others in the same discipline, as  demonstrated by the next two articles.&nbsp;  The fourth article below shows that other, and different,  efforts to bring greater order to the ever-exploding volume of data on the Web  are also ongoing. How important is better organization and search accessibility?  One metric was provided at a recent NIST workshop, as reported in the last article below.  According to specialists there, new digital data equal to the entire U.S. Library of Congress is created every…15 minutes.</em></p></td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://technology.guardian.co.uk/weekly/story/0,,1747327,00.html" target="_hdl">Spread the word, and join it up</a></strong><br>
                <strong>The Guardian.com.uk April 7, 2006</strong>&nbsp;...The system that should  revolutionise online searching is the &quot;semantic web&quot;, where online  data is marked up with indications of its meaning, rather than simply its  appearance and links, as currently happens on the world wide web....Sir Tim  Berners-Lee - better known as the inventor of the world wide web - also  originated the idea of the semantic web, which he calls &quot;the web of  data&quot;. But this new brainchild is finding it much harder to take off. <a href="http://technology.guardian.co.uk/weekly/story/0,,1747327,00.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/71954" target="_hdl">Vikings set out to conquer Semantic Web</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Heise Online.de April 13, 2006</strong>&nbsp;German scientists are working on a  project they call Wikinger (German for &quot;Viking&quot;) based on the concept  of Wikipedia to provide virtual knowledge networking in addition to the classic  exchange of knowledge at Congresses. The goal of the project is to create a  domain-neutral platform for scientists to allow them to perform research in  knowledge bases regardless of where they are and to generate new knowledge via  the Internet in collaboration. To this end, techniques from the Semantic Web  are being used. <a href="http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/71954">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.bio-itworld.com/newsitems/2006/april/04-10-06-news-sematic-web" target="_hdl">Spearheading the Semantic Web</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Catherine Varmazis</strong><br>
                <strong>BIO-ITWorld.com April 10, 2006</strong>&nbsp;BOSTON &ndash; Sharing their passion for  the Semantic Web at the Bio-IT World Life Sciences Conference + Expo session on  Tuesday were several prominent leaders of the movement. Providing a clinical  perspective was Tonya Hongsermeier of Partners Healthcare, who said the  Semantic Web is necessary for knowledge management because &ldquo;the market is  balking at healthcare inflation.&rdquo; She said eight datapoints are now kept for  each patient (age, height, weight, etc.), but with new tests and personalized  medicine, the number could balloon to 3000. The Semantic Web can reduce the  cost and liability of knowledge management, said Hongsermeier, and is a  critical component of translational medicine going forward. <a href="http://www.bio-itworld.com/newsitems/2006/april/04-10-06-news-sematic-web">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.fcw.com/article92807-04-03-06-Print" target="_hdl">Framework could aid global information exchange</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Aliya Sternstein</strong><br>
                <strong>FCW.com April 4, 2006</strong>&nbsp;An open-standards group has created a  framework that could facilitate the global exchange of information among  organizations. The naming system could benefit a wide range of disciplines,  from disaster response to medical research. The Open Group&rsquo;s Universal Data  Element Framework (UDEF) has the potential to hasten information exchange by  indexing the world&rsquo;s datasets &mdash; from e-commerce services to government  registries and medical research databases &mdash; in one universally shared semantic  repository. <a href="http://www.fcw.com/article92807-04-03-06-Print">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://news.com.com/2100-1032_3-6060741.html" target="_hdl">Google unveils Web-based calendar app</a></strong><br>
                  <strong>Elinor Mills</strong><br>
                  <strong>CNET.News.com April 13, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The beta version of Google Calendar,  which can be accessed without a Gmail account, enables users to search for and  add events from within the program or through Web sites that use open standards  for calendars. Such sites are invited to add Google Calendar buttons next to  events they list....The application interoperates with other calendaring  programs that use Apple Computer's iCal or XML standards....the company is  opening up the application programming interface so that outside developers can  use it to build third-party programs that will work with Google Calendar data,  ... <a href="http://news.com.com/2100-1032_3-6060741.html">...Full Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/04/05/business/software.php" target="_hdl">Sharing Lego blocks: Modular software  reshapes the computing landscape</a></strong><br>
                <strong>John Markoff</strong><br>
                <strong>The New York Times April 7, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The Internet is entering its Lego  era. Blocks of interchangeable software components are proliferating on the  Web, and developers are joining them together to create a potentially infinite  array of useful new programs. This new software represents a marked departure  from the inflexible, at times unwieldy, programs of the past, which were  designed to run on individual computers <a href="http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/04/05/business/software.php">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.nist.gov/public_affairs/techbeat/tb2006_0330.htm#bytes" target="_hdl">Bytes by the Quintillion For Today  and Tomorrow</a></strong><br>
                <strong>NIST Techbeat April 4, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Engineers and information specialists  from government, industry and academia agreed this month at a National  Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) workshop that immediate action is  needed to keep vast amounts of digital knowledge from disappearing into  cyberspace or becoming in 200, or even 20 years, as incomprehensible as the  markings on Babylonian cuneiform tablets. According to estimates offered at the  conference, the world churns out new digital information equivalent to the  entire collection of the U.S. Library of Congress every 15 minutes. <a href="http://www.nist.gov/public_affairs/techbeat/tb2006_0330.htm#bytes">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
