                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>Shockwaves from the  epicenter:</em></strong><em>&nbsp; It's now been seven months since  Massachusetts committed to ODF, and the reverberations of that decision  continue to echo.&nbsp; This month's news  included the continuing fast growth of the ODF Alliance, which was formed to  help educate governments on the virtues of ODF.&nbsp; Only a month old, its membership has almost quadrupled (for more,  see <a href="http://www.consortiuminfo.org/standardsblog/article.php?story=20060419061204507">this  entry</a> at the Standards Blog). Meanwhile, a second open source office suite  was released in an ODF-compliant form, the State of Minnesota saw its own  &quot;open formats&quot; bill introduced by a state legislator, and at  LinuxWorld, people were scratching their heads, trying to figure out what it  all means. &nbsp;You can follow continuing  ODF news at the Standards Blog.</em></p></td>
