                  <td colspan="2" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>Without strong network neutrality enforcement,  this bill gives the cable and phone companies a green light to...create a  second-class Internet</em></strong><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;[April 2,  2006]</em></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td width="46" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td width="455" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p>Gary Bachula,  Internet2 vice president of external relations, criticizing the just enacted  Communications Opportunity, Promotion and Enhancement Act of 2006<a href="https://mail.internet2.edu/wws/arc/i2-news/2006-03/msg00005.html">...Full Story</a></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <table width="605"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>A clear and present danger?</em></strong><em>&nbsp; One of the great advantages of the Internet  and the Web is that they permit free and open exchanges of ideas and  information (at least in most countries), making equal Internet access a vital  service, especially for the otherwise disadvantaged.&nbsp; However, in the U.S. broadband services were deregulated, and  according to EDUCAUSE and Internet2, as reported in the following article, a  new bill would remove the ability of the FCC to ensure the openness of the  Internet, thereby permitting discrimination in the provision of services to go unpunished.</em></p></td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="https://mail.internet2.edu/wws/arc/i2-news/2006-03/msg00005.html" target="_hdl">Draft Telecom Legislation Falls Short  of Preserving Internet Openness</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Press Release</strong><br>
                <strong>EDUCause and Internet2 April 2, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Washington, D.C.- The U.S.  House of Representatives' staff yesterday released the latest version of  legislation dubbed, &quot;The Communications Opportunity, Promotion and  Enhancement Act of 2006,&quot; which aims to rewrite US telecommunications  laws. According to EDUCAUSE and Internet2, while the bill takes some positive  steps in helping to encourage the expansion of broadband networks to consumer  homes as well as to open the door to the creation of municipal broadband  networks, the bill completely lacks critical language that would maintain and  support the vital principle of network neutrality. In doing so, the bill falls  far short of serving the needs of the country's citizens and instead provides  cable and phone companies with the authority they seek for the creation of  discriminatory networks. <a href="https://mail.internet2.edu/wws/arc/i2-news/2006-03/msg00005.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
